\begin{title}
Optical Properties
\end{title}

\begin{title}
Optical Transparency in the Near-Infrared (NIR) Region
\end{title}

Whereas the electronic transition causes the absorption in the UV region, the harmonics and their coupling of the stretching vibration of chem- ical bonds cause the absorption in the near-infra- red region. The carbon–hydrogen (C—H) and oxy- gen–hydrogen (O—H) bonds are reported to strongly affect the absorption in the near-infrared region.13 The low absorption in both the 1.3- and 1.55-mm wavelengths, which are used in optical

\begin{caption}
Figure 1 TGA thermograms of polyimides with a heating rate of 10°C/min in a nitrogen atmosphere.
